rijk","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"about 1115–":"about 1115–Deceased","1115–Male":"1115–Deceased","1115–1145":"1115–1145","1140–Male":"1140–Deceased","1145–Male":"1145–Deceased","1115–Female":"1115–Deceased","about 1140":"about 1140","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","about 1115":"about 1115","about 1145":"about 1145","About 1145":"about 1145","1140":"1140","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","of Cloch-faen, Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Hywel","type":"LAST","meanings":["A Welsh name. Some write the name Hoel, which they render 'lordly;' if so, it may come from huail, a vice-regent, regent. Arthur derives the surname Howell from Corn. -Brit, houl, the sun; and he adds, high, exalted.' But Hywel is rather from hywel, conspicuous."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Mawd","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval vernacular form of   Matilda .  This form was characteristically Low German (i.e. including medieval Dutch and Flemish). The wife of  William the Conqueror , who bore this name, was the daughter of  Baldwin , Count of Flanders. In Flemish and Dutch the letter <i>-t-</i> was generally lost when it occurred between vowels, giving forms such as <i>Ma(h)auld</i>. <i>Maud</i> or <i>Matilda</i> was also the name of the daughter (  1102–67 ) of  Henry I  of England; she was married early in life to the Holy Roman Emperor  Henry V , and later disputed the throne of England with her cousin  Stephen . In  1128  she married  Geoffrey , Count of Anjou. A medieval chronicler commented, ‘she was a good woman, but she had little bliss with him’. The name <i>Maud</i> became quite common in England in the 19th century, when its popularity was influenced in part by  Tennyson's  poem Maud, published in  1855 , but has not been much used since the early decades of the 20th century."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ferch","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German: variant of   Ferg  . Compare   Verch  .","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förtsch</b> (see   Foertsch  ).","Probably also an Americanized form of German <b>Förch</b> (see   Foerch  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Ferg","meanings":["From the vocabulary word denoting the plant (Old English <i>fearn</i>). Modern use of this word as a given name dates from the 19th century, when it is also recorded occasionally as a boy's name in the United States. In some instances the given name may be a transferred use of the surname derived in the medieval period from the vocabulary word."]}]},{"name":"Rhys","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional name meaning ‘ardour’; borne in the Middle Ages by various rulers in south-west Wales, including  Rhys ap Tewdur  (  d. 1093 ) and  Rhys ap Gruffudd  (  1132–97 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Reece","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Rhys . The name is now in widespread and frequent use outside Wales, in many cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the given name."]},{"name":"Rees","meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Rhys ap Hywel was born about 1115, in Wales. She married Lord Hywel Seisyll about 1145, in Wales. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in her hometown."},"et":{"about 1115–":"umbes 1115–Surnud","1115–Male":"1115–Surnud","1115–1145":"1115–1145","1140–Male":"1140–Surnud","1145–Male":"1145–Surnud","1115–Female":"1115–Surnud","about 1140":"umbes 1140","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","about 1115":"umbes 1115","about 1145":"umbes 1145","About 1145":"umbes 1145","1140":"1140","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","of Cloch-faen, Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"about 1115–":"noin 1115–Kuollut","1115–Male":"1115–Kuollut","1115–1145":"1115–1145","1140–Male":"1140–Kuollut","1145–Male":"1145–Kuollut","1115–Female":"1115–Kuollut","about 1140":"noin 1140","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","about 1115":"noin 1115","about 1145":"noin 1145","About 1145":"noin 1145","1140":"1140","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales","Wales":"Wales","of Cloch-faen, Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta"},"fr":{"about 1115–":"environ 1115–Décédée","1115–Male":"1115–Décédé","1115–1145":"1115–1145","1140–Male":"1140–Décédé","1145–Male":"1145–Décédé","1115–Female":"1115–Décédée","about 1140":"environ 1140","1115":"1115","1145":"1145","about 1115":"environ 1115","about 1145":"environ 1145","About 1145":"environ 1145","1140":"1140","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Galles","Wales":"Galles","of Cloch-faen, Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Wales":"Llangurig, Montgomeryshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","Llangamarch, Breconshire, Wales, United Kingdom":"Llangamarch, Breconshire, Pays de Galles, Royaume-Uni","lifeSummary":"Mawd ferch Rhys ap Hywel est née environ 1115, à Galles. Elle a épousé Lord Hywel Seisyll environ 